## MODULE 3: Helmholtz-Hodge decomposition (src/solver/hodge.py)

Decompose the measured displacement field into its divergence-free
(shear wave) and curl-free (compressional wave) components.

### 3a. 2D Hodge decomposition
For a 2D vector displacement field u = (u_x, u_y):

    u = ∇φ (curl-free) + ∇⊥ψ (div-free)

In Fourier space:
    k = (kx, ky),  k² = kx²+ky²
    φ̂(k) = (kx·Ûx + ky·Ûy) / k²          [scalar potential]
    ψ̂(k) = (kx·Ûy - ky·Ûx) / k²          [stream function]

    Divergence-free component:
    Ûx_df = Ûx - kx·φ̂  =  ky²·Ûx/k² - kx·ky·Ûy/k²
    Ûy_df = Ûy - ky·φ̂  =  kx²·Ûy/k² - kx·ky·Ûx/k²

    Curl-free component:
    Ûx_cf = kx·φ̂
    Ûy_cf = ky·φ̂

Function: hodge_decompose_2d(ux, uy, dx)
  Inputs:  ux, uy — complex (N,N) displacement components
  Returns: dict with keys:
           'div_free': (ux_df, uy_df) — shear wave component
           'curl_free': (ux_cf, uy_cf) — compressional component
           'phi': scalar potential field
           'psi': stream function field

### 3b. Directional filter (TSM directional decomposition)
This is the key TSM operation: select wave components propagating
parallel to the lesion surface (perpendicular to outward normal n̂).

Function: directional_filter_tsm(ux_df, uy_df, boundary_normals, dx,
                                  n_angles=36, delta_threshold=0.3)
  For each propagation direction θ in linspace(0, π, n_angles):
    k̂ = (cos θ, sin θ)
    filter_weight = max(0, 1 - |k̂ · n̂(x,y)| / delta_threshold)
    Apply directional bandpass in Fourier space

  Returns: u_tsm — displacement field retaining only tangentially
                    propagating shear waves (the TSM signal)
           G_tsm_map — local stiffness from TSM-filtered waves (MIP)

